 <h1>cfenv</h1>
 <h2>Groom your app's CFML environment.</h2>
  <div class="code">
    bash &lt;(curl -s <a href="http://cfenv.co/scripts/install.sh">http://cfenv.co/scripts/install.sh</a>)
  </div>
  <h3>Run this command in your terminal to install cfenv on your machine.</h3>
  <hr />
  <div class="information">
    <div class="info-item">
      <h2>Why should I use it?</h2>
      <p>
        Use cfenv to pick a Railo version for your application and guarantee that your development environment matches production.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Configuration free.</strong> Run our simple installer from ANY computer, and you'll be developing a new CFML application within roughly a minute.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Truly empowering.</strong> Specify your app's Railo version once, in a single file. Keep all your teammates on the same page. No headaches running apps on different versions of Railo. Just Worksâ„¢ from the command line. Override the Railo version anytime: just set an environment variable.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>It just works.</strong> cfenv is concerned solely with managing and switching Railo versions. It's simple and predictable.
      </p>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <div class="info-item">
      <h2>What if I use Adobe ColdFusion (and not Railo)?</h2>
      <p>
        Using Adobe ColdFusion is not a problem generally, but we understand your concerns.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not currently have support for Adobe ColdFusion as of yet but we're working on a good solid method for using cfenv to install and manage ACF versions within your development workflow.  We're thinking it's definitely possible.
      </p>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <div class="info-item">
      <h2>Does this work on Windows?</h2>
      <p>
        Although we do not personally use Windows to develop on, we're trying to make cfenv as usable as possible across all platforms.
      </p>
      <p>
        We have not done any REAL testing on Windows with cfenv but we suspect it will work best in it's current state when ran within cygwin or the like.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <hr />
